h3. Steps to reproduce

# Login to JIRA as an Administrator;
# Create an Epic in a project;
# Now create a new issues and choose a different project;
# Click on the dropdown of the "Epic Link" field;
# The Epic created before in a different project is listed in this project as well;

h3. What is needed

We want the "Epic Link" field to display only Epics from the selected project.

{{As an administrator I would like to quickly add a set of dates e.g. US Bank Holidays, to a board's non-working days}}



Original summary: Button to add US bank holidays to non-working days
Original description: As an administrator of LawGives, I would like a quick button to automatically add all US Bank Holidays to the non-working days.  (See screen shot)

h5. Steps to replicate:

- Create 3 Issues in a clean board: ISSUE-1, ISSUE-2 and ISSUE-3 keeping the same order in the Backlog;
- Perform a JQL search of the "ISSUE" project ordered by Rank - it will show ISSUE-1, ISSUE-2 and ISSUE-3;
- Now create a Sprint in this board and add the ISSUE-2 to this Sprint;
- Perform a JQL search of the "ISSUE" project ordered by Rank:

h5. Actual behavior:
The filter result will show ISSUE-1, ISSUE-2 and ISSUE-3;

h5. Expected behavior:
The filter result should bring ISSUE-2, ISSUE-1 and ISSUE-3;

The priority of an Issue in a Sprint should be higher than an Issue in the Backlog, since the users will work on the Sprint, and not in the backlog. However, if you search for those issues ordering by the Rank to use as a report, for example, it will show us an incorrect view of the Issues.

h3. Expected behavior:
Being possible to edit any date through the "Backlog" view, regardless of manually editing the field or selecting the date in the calendar picker.

h3. Actual behavior:
Field leaves the "Inline Editing" mode whenever you open the calendar picker or click on any part of the date to have it changed.

h3. Steps to Reproduce:
# Create a version in an Agile-enabled project;
# Open the "Backlog" view on the project's Board;
# Expand the "Versions" sidebar;
# Try to edit any date on the version;
#* Calendar picker
### Opens the pop-up;
### You can select the date, but the field isn't in "Inline Editing" mode anymore, therefore no changes are saved;
#* Editing the field itself 
### When clicking on any part of the date to edit, the field leaves "Inline Editing" mode, therefore not making it possible to modify;

h3. Workaround:

h4. #1
Edit versions' dates through the "Versions" panel inside the "Project Administration" page.

h4. #2
# Activate "Inline Editing" by clicking the date;
# Use "Delete" to erase all the date;
# Type in a new date;

h6.Summary

The default name for the new sprints is derived from the most recent planned sprint associated with the board. This, however, accounts for sprints that were created in different boards and aren't displayed in the _Backlog_ view.

h6.Steps to reproduce

# create Board A, and there a new sprint named "A 1";
# click *Create Sprint* in Board A again - the default name for it will be "A 2";
# create Board B, with a filter overlapping with that of board A, so that some issues show up in both of them;
# create a "B 1" sprint in Board B, and add an issue included in both boards to it;
# get back to Board A - now "B 1" sprint will be displayed there too;
# transition the issue edited in point 4 to move it out of Board A backlog;
# refresh Board A - the transitioned issue won't show in the _Backlog_ view anymore, and so neither does sprint "B 1";
# click *Create Sprint* in Board A again.

*Expected result:* default name for the new sprint is "A 2".
*Actual result:* default name for the new sprint is "B 2".

While technically this behaviour may be correct, it's is counter-intuitive and confusing. Users would expect the new sprint to be named after the most recent one displayed in the _Backlog_ view. When JIRA Agile determines a sprint to base the new sprint name on, it should either:
- pick the most recent planned sprint created in the current board, or;
- pick the most recent planned sprint displayed in the current _Backlog_ view.

