When adding issues (Issues in Epic) with time estimates to an epic, the estimate doesn't summarize it and/or calculate it in the epic level.

This should work like tasks and sub-tasks where on tasks you have a summary of the estimates and can also include the sub-tasks values on it.

Viewing a Version Report and clicking on 'view <Version Name> in Issue Navigator' sends you to the Issue Navigator with a query similar to the following:

{{https://instancename/issues/?jql=fixVersion=%22Latest%20Version%22%20AND%20project=EX}}

If the Project Key has a JQL reserved word (for example 'IF' or 'AND') then it will not display any issues in the Issue Navigator as it throws a JQL error. Putting the Issue Key in quotes return the correct results. The Report will still work however.

When a Sprint is started with a future time and/or date in the 'Start Date', it's shown in Agile as active, but changes made to its scope aren't recorded until the selected date/time passes.

h6.Steps to reproduce
# create a sprint and start it;
# in the 'Start Sprint' dialog box, in the _Start Date_ field, select a time in the future and click *Start*;
# go back to the Backlog view, and add an issue to the 'active' sprint;
# a warning dialog will be displayed: "Sprint scope will be affected by this action", click *Confirm* to proceed;
# move an issue in the sprint to the rightmost board column to complete it;
# go to the Report view to view the Burndown Chart.

*Result:* the initial sprint scope in the Burndown Chart is adjusted as if the changes were made before the sprint was started. The completed issue isn't displayed as burnt down during the sprint.

I'm not sure what the expected result would be, but there seems to be no consistency here. On one hand, all changes to issues are recognised as if they happened before the sprint started - which makes sense, as the Start Date hasn't passed yet. On the other hand, though, the sprint is shown as active in the board, and a warning about the scope change is displayed when adding issues to it. The approach to sprints starting in the future should be clarified.

h3. Expected behavior:
Have "Remaining Estimate" decreased when moving a sub-task out of a Sprint

h3. Actual behavior:
When looking at the "Burn-down Chart" it's clear that the "Remaining Estimate" is not decreased correctly, no negative time is applied.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a sub-task and assign it a Time Estimate;
# Add the sub-task to a sprint;
# Start the sprint;
# Move the sub-task out of the sprint;

h3. Workaround:
Zero out the "Remaining Estimate" of the sub-task before moving it, then re-apply the time after move has been completed.
